Notebook[{
Cell["Curvatures Tutorial", "Title",ExpressionUUID->"caf05339-4328-474d-b0ee-c59ebe1a99f8"],

Cell["\<\
Three discrete Ricci-curvature engines on graphs: Forman-Ricci (combinatorial \
2-complex curvature), Ollivier-Ricci (Wasserstein-1 contraction of uniform \
neighbourhood measures), and Wolfram-Ricci (volume-comparison scalar at each \
vertex / radius). All three return Associations keyed by edge or vertex; all \
three feed into the Method -> CurvatureMinimizing branch of FindSegment / \
FindLine / ExtendSegment.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"53c96404-b536-4522-831a-77e429a70153"],

Cell["Setup", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"155e67ad-5a75-435b-b344-8544d9bbe0e0"],

Cell["Needs[\"WolframInstitute`SyntheticInfrageometry`\"]", "Code",ExpressionUUID->"03b7de6e-f10e-40ee-9cf4-76db8aa5b6d6"],

Cell["Forman-Ricci curvature", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"ca9cf44a-11fd-42b6-8cab-ceb2f6152e3b"],

Cell["\<\
Edge-level discrete curvature derived from Forman's combinatorial Bochner \
formula. Two flavours: Simple (1-skeleton, F(e) = 4 - deg(u) - deg(v)) and \
Triangles (every 3-cycle filled as a 2-cell, F(e) = 4 - deg(u) - deg(v) + 3 \
#triangles(e)).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8d1ac72c-5aa3-4cf3-bfea-477e844039c3"],

Cell["FormanRicci[GridGraph[{3, 3}]]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"a6a1f9a0-f33f-4229-af04-84597dd0d894"],

Cell["FormanRicci[CompleteGraph[5], Method -> \"Triangles\"]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"73524474-1bb8-4044-8307-12d8bbd8d752"],

Cell["\<\
A complete graph K_5 has lots of triangles per edge -- the Triangles flavour \
gives strongly positive Forman-Ricci everywhere, matching the spherical \
character of K_5.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ab4e4836-bbd3-48bc-8a95-25bdd0d34381"],

Cell["Ollivier-Ricci curvature", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"ac29e4f6-a61c-484d-aae7-7108048299ed"],

Cell["\<\
Edge curvature kappa(u, v) = 1 - W_1(mu_u, mu_v) / d(u, v) where mu_x is the \
uniform distribution on the open neighbourhood N(x), W_1 is the Wasserstein-1 \
distance under graph distance, and the idleness alpha is 0. Computed by \
linear-programming the optimal transport.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c1d65c1e-9953-4bb5-9eaf-6871c9807358"],

Cell["OllivierRicci[GridGraph[{3, 3}]]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"2d344bb1-b3aa-4f77-a60c-df433235cb3b"],

Cell["Trees have negative Ollivier-Ricci on their internal edges:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"7753db6c-bbe6-42ee-8a94-a0293a9ad805"],

Cell["OllivierRicci[CompleteBinaryTree[2]]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"ad4f2157-f549-4828-ae2f-c444f4db2842"],

Cell["Cliques have positive Ollivier-Ricci:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"d5fd1982-499b-4da1-ae5c-bffe5aa2fd62"],

Cell["OllivierRicci[CompleteGraph[4]]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"acf2d540-2fb1-475c-95f0-6db49c8139d0"],

Cell["Wolfram-Ricci curvature", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"c2f6b63a-c4d7-4cd6-8eea-15ab1dfcad85"],

Cell["\<\
Vertex-level discrete Ricci scalar from volume comparison: R(v, r) = \
6(d+2)/r^2 (1 - V(r)/V_E(d, r)), where V(r) is the ball volume and V_E is the \
Euclidean volume. The dimension d can be auto-detected from local volume \
growth or set explicitly.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3db7f09a-c342-4090-9e8e-bb4a2b393ae8"],

Cell["Mean over per-vertex valid radius range:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"e2a75c7b-ec7f-4ee5-b26c-3de72b1fe914"],

Cell["WolframRicci[GridGraph[{4, 4}]]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"02d3a36c-0b97-49de-9c03-fabc94cee31b"],

Cell["Single radius:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"f9ae503a-6222-45a0-a91d-fee0024af45c"],

Cell["WolframRicci[GridGraph[{4, 4}], 2]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"dd532b5e-c061-4ae2-8715-ff6cc6c44b30"],

Cell["Explicit dimension:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"be334515-2f60-496a-86cc-bdcc1eeb19f2"],

Cell["WolframRicci[GridGraph[{5, 5}], \"Dimension\" -> 2]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"eddf3e0b-7bbd-4a16-a396-5ed679fdb478"],

Cell["Curvature-minimizing path enumeration", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"f9a0fbc0-70ac-4af8-9617-3f1fa9c47b87"],

Cell["\<\
The three engines plug into the Method -> CurvatureMinimizing branch of \
FindSegment / FindLine / ExtendSegment. The frontier sweep, at every step, \
restricts candidates to the minimisers of an edge-level kappa.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"841f509b-362c-481a-b304-b39c5d84828e"],

Cell["FindSegment with Forman as the curvature engine:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"1338d80d-24bf-4095-8a72-35bec6c0ba84"],

Cell["\<\
FindSegment[GridGraph[{3, 3}], 1, 9, All, Method -> \"CurvatureMinimizing\"]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"c73b6684-0b21-443b-a0a3-aac443a291fb"],

Cell["\<\
FindSegment with the Wolfram engine -- the frontier prefers cells with \
most-negative scalar Ricci, the most-expanding direction:\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"d3a70678-6489-4d07-97d8-d21703a83ad2"],

Cell["\<\
FindSegment[GridGraph[{3, 3}], 1, 9, All, Method -> {\"CurvatureMinimizing\", \
\"Curvature\" -> {\"Wolfram\"}}]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"aade264d-1d79-4a92-a028-8e5121556b01"],

Cell["The Forman-Triangles flavour and an explicit pruning beam:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"039433b5-fd8d-4d7e-bf7e-75cbaa33c6f0"],

Cell["\<\
FindSegment[GridGraph[{4, 4}], 1, 16, UpTo[5], Method -> \
{\"CurvatureMinimizing\", \"Curvature\" -> {\"Forman\", Method -> \"Triangles\
\"}, \"Pruning\" -> 5}]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"6b506f89-f0a3-494d-98b4-b0ba01da086d"],

Cell["Visualization", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"98f336ed-61ca-44de-9e40-2c5143ac3bc6"],

Cell["\<\
Curvature is most useful when you can see it. Render an edge-curvature \
Association on the graph by colouring edges:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d00caaec-3867-4a78-bb71-485aad8cb8bf"],

Cell["\<\
With[{g = GridGraph[{4, 4}], curv = OllivierRicci[GridGraph[{4, 4}]]}, \
Graph[g, EdgeStyle -> KeyValueMap[#1 -> \
ColorData[\"DarkRainbow\"][Rescale[#2, MinMax[Values[curv]]]] &, curv], \
EdgeShapeFunction -> \"Line\"]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"29054124-1ddd-4b7f-8f37-635e97cad2ac"],

Cell["See also", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"dc259c4c-fae4-47f4-b64b-4d02b0aa4b40"],

Cell["CurvaturesGuide -- categorical overview.", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"dcd37649-b4ed-44c8-8e71-10535528a463"],

Cell["\<\
EuclideanGeometryGuide -- FindSegment / FindLine / ExtendSegment Method axis \
(where curvature drives the path enumeration).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"4f754851-c494-4694-a5fb-94be50d9d5a0"],

Cell["References", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"7834d309-f9f5-46e6-8380-d6e7054c339c"],

Cell["\<\
Forman, Bochner's Method for Cell Complexes and Combinatorial Ricci \
Curvature, Discrete Comput. Geom. 29, 2003.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"f3b06dd7-b73b-40a1-a1d5-e9af5c2c6a07"],

Cell["\<\
Ollivier, Ricci Curvature of Markov Chains on Metric Spaces, J. Funct. Anal. \
256, 2009, https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0701886\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"585ca441-ecad-4453-b0e0-e8e959b423ce"],

Cell["\<\
Wolfram, A Class of Models with the Potential to Represent Fundamental \
Physics, https://arxiv.org/abs/2004.08210\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"cabe44a5-d1de-4e0d-a8ef-ad83923e06e4"],

Cell["\<\
Sandhu, Georgiou and Tannenbaum, Ricci Curvature: An Economic Indicator for \
Market Fragility and Systemic Risk, Sci. Adv. 2(5), 2016 (Ollivier on real \
networks).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"728ea79b-0828-4460-a702-b40c6d1f39fd"],

Cell["Constant-curvature substrates: locally homogeneous graphs", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"0595fc6a-a31f-4d25-80b9-b84bf7f154b1"],

Cell["\<\
The discrete analogue of a constant-curvature manifold is a graph in which \
every r-ball is graph-isomorphic to every other -- the local data the \
curvature sees is the same at every vertex. The cleanest realisation is a \
vertex-transitive graph: Aut(G) acts transitively on vertices, so \
left-translation by any group element is a graph automorphism, hence \
WolframRicci is pointwise constant at every radius. Cayley graphs of finite \
groups are the broadest natural family.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"aad029ab-f47f-4fc3-a73a-9ba2227da1f0"],

Cell["\<\
A discrete flat torus -- the Cartesian product of two cycles -- has \
WolframRicci constant across all vertices.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"74c6b2a0-17b9-4f94-9527-096827777d55"],

Cell["\<\
Union @ Values @ WolframRicci[ GraphProduct[ CycleGraph[ 5 ], CycleGraph[ 5 \
], \"Cartesian\" ], \"Dimension\" -> 2 ]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"9537702e-0594-4228-8938-a58790519b07"],

Cell["\<\
A circulant graph -- the canonical one-dimensional Cayley graph of Z_n -- \
gives the same constancy.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"5f26dc09-9e22-4510-a0bb-72c6e0546539"],

Cell["\<\
Union @ Values @ WolframRicci[ CirculantGraph[ 12, { 1, 2 } ] ]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"0d676412-2769-4db6-951e-edc35398b56e"],

Cell["\<\
A non-vertex-transitive graph -- here a path -- shows curvature varying with \
position.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"bde7dd09-288b-4dcd-b316-6c87e7bc77cd"],

Cell["WolframRicci[ PathGraph @ Range[ 7 ] ]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"407acbd7-61c2-482a-8991-c34f694b968c"],

Cell["\<\
In between strict vertex-transitivity and arbitrary irregularity sits the \
broader notion of r-local homogeneity: every r-ball is graph-isomorphic for \
some specific r, possibly without a global automorphism group. The girth \
criterion gives a clean recipe -- any d-regular graph of girth at least 2 r + \
2 has all r-balls equal to the depth-r d-regular tree, automatically. \
WolframRicci at radius r is then constant; at radius r + 1 it may not be. \
This makes the radius window in WolframRicci[g, {rmin, rmax}] a knob for the \
scale at which the substrate looks locally homogeneous.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"060c017d-d40d-40ed-a07d-b391c9545f0f"]
},
FrontEndVersion->"14.3 for Mac OS X ARM (64-bit) (July 8, 2025)",
StyleDefinitions->"Default.nb",
ExpressionUUID->"5f03c5ed-44f9-4bcd-91fa-2cb3d45e5b95"
]
